# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The **Alliance for Direct Democracy in Europe**, abbreviated to **ADDE**, was a European political party founded in 2014.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] It was composed of parties belonging to the Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy (EFDD) group in the European Parliament (EP).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The dominant national party in the ADDE was the UK Independence Party (UKIP), providing 21 of the party's 27 members of the European Parliament (MEPs) elected in 2014.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] A further three UKIP MEPs chose not to participate in the ADDE.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] In 2015, the ADDE was recognised by the European Parliament and its grant maximum from the EP was set at €1,241,725, with an additional €730,053 for its affiliated political foundation, the *Initiative for Direct Democracy*.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] ADDE was closed down in 2016 after an auditors' inquiry found misspending of EU funds.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe] The party was legally dissolved on 24 May 2017.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The **Alliance for Europe of the Nations** was a European political party that gathered conservative and national-conservative political parties from across the continent.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The AEN was founded in 2002, designed to complement the existing Union for Europe of the Nations group in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] Moves towards establishing standardised funding block grants for European political parties were at this point well afoot, and the parties affiliated with UEN required a corresponding organisation to take advantage of them.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] Almost immediately upon its founding, the AEN began to decline in terms of membership and influence.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] At its first meeting, participants included the Czech Civic Democratic Party, Portuguese CDS-PP, Israeli Likud, Irish Fianna Fáil, Italian National Alliance and the Greek Popular Orthodox Rally, all of which later left the organisation.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] The AEN had a broadly national-conservative political line, but many members were uncomfortable with this.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] There was a strong movement for the centrist Fianna Fáil to leave AEN and join the European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party, which it did on 17 April 2009.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-europe-of-the-nations] After those realignments, there were too few AEN member parties left to retain its EU-funded status as a European political party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The **Alliance for Peace and Freedom** (**APF**) is a far-right European political alliance and former European political party founded on 4 February 2015.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The main member parties were involved in the defunct **European National Front**.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The alliance wishes to establish a network of nationalist movements across Europe that will cooperate to strengthen their shared ideals.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It cooperates and supports other nationalist groups across Europe that are not members, these include former party members Golden Dawn, Tricolour Flame, Alternative for Sweden and the ELAM.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The alliance is described as neo-Nazi by several newspapers, and neo-fascist by others.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The group works for "a Europe of sovereign nations in which the independent states work together on a confederated basis", and for the perennity and the safeguarding of ancestral European traditions such as the Christian tradition.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The Europa Terra Nostra is the official European political foundation of the APF.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The ETN was founded 3 July 2015 in Berlin where it continues to operate as the official think-tank of the APF and serves as the European framework for national foundations/think-tanks recognised by APF member-parties.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF works to co-ordinate European nationalist parties across the continent.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It helped establish the Italy for the Italians coalition composed of APF member New Force along with Tricolour Flame.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] In 2017 the APF aided in the formation of the National Identity Bloc in Europe coalition, APF members, United Romania Party and Noua Dreaptă joined forces with the Greater Romania Party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] In 2019 The APF played a part in forming the ADÑ Identidad Española coalition, composed of APF member National Democracy, FE-JONS, Spanish Alternative and La Falange.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party also maintains contacts with the former leader of the National Front, Jean-Marie Le Pen, who was expelled from his party in 2015.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] He joined the group in March 2018 as an Honorary Chairman and held this position until his death in January 2025.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF maintains contacts with conservative circles in Russia with the group being invited to conferences hosted by the Kremlin.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party supports Vladimir Putin and United Russia's leadership of Russia, especially in the Russo-Ukrainian War and Syrian Civil War.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The party is supportive of Alexander Lukashenko and maintains contacts with the Liberal Democratic Party of Belarus.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The APF strongly supports Serbian nationalists and is opposed to international recognition of Kosovo, it has worked in the past with the Serbian Radical Party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] On 26 September 2021, the APF held a conference in Belgrade hosted by the Serbian Right.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] It maintained friendly relations with the Syrian Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party government with deputy chairman, Nick Griffin being invited to Syria by Bashar al-Assad multiple times as an ambassador.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] Meetings between the party and the Syrian Social Nationalist Party have been held with the AFP publicly supporting the SSNP.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] The group maintains contacts with Hezbollah and has hosted at least one meeting with Hezbollah leaders.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-for-peace-and-freedom] Michel Aoun, then president of Lebanon, received a delegation of the APF in 2018 and in 2019, and the group claims to have been in regular contact with him and his party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The **Alliance of European National Movements** (**AENM**) was a European political party that was formed in Budapest on 24 October 2009 by a number of ultranationalist and far-right parties from countries in Europe.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] AENM's founding members were Jobbik (the alliance was established during their sixth party congress), France's National Front, Italy's Tricolour Flame, Sweden's National Democrats and Belgium's National Front.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2011, the National Front withdrew from AENM and joined the European Alliance for Freedom (EAF).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2014, the All-Ukrainian Union "Freedom" terminated its observer status in the AENM, due to many members of the bloc showing support for Russia in the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In February 2016, Jobbik cut all of its affiliation with AENM, and the president of AENM Béla Kovács left Jobbik.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In November 2009, the British National Party claimed that AENM had been extended to nine parties, but this information was not confirmed by AENM President Bruno Gollnisch in 2012.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At a press conference held in Strasbourg on 16 June 2010, the political leadership of AENM was confirmed as follows: President Bruno Gollnisch, Vice President Nick Griffin, Treasurer Béla Kovács and Secretary General Valerio Cignetti.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2011 the National Front withdrew from AENM and joined the European Alliance for Freedom.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] However, Gollnisch and Jean-Marie Le Pen maintained their position in the organisation.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In October 2013, Marine Le Pen requested that Gollnisch and Jean-Marie Le Pen leave their positions in the AENM in order to join the more moderate EAF and so unify the French National Front under the EAF banner.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Marine Le Pen has tried to "de-demonize" the party, i.e. to give it a more acceptable image.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Cooperation with the openly racist and antisemitic parties present in AENM was seen as contradictory to these aims.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] On November 7, the two declared they have followed the request and left AENM.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] This also meant the end of Gollnisch's term as the AENM's chairman, a place occupied by Béla Kovács since January 2014.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In the spring of 2013, Svoboda lost its observer status after a conflict with other member groups over its policies towards ethnic minorities in the West of Ukraine.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Béla Kovács, leader of the alliance, had served as an observer at the 2014 Donbass parliamentary election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2014, there were accusations against Chairman Kovács that he or his wife were working for the Russian intelligence service.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2015 the European Parliament lifted Kovács immunity.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In September 2020, he was cleared of the charge of espionage.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] However, he had worked with the Russian secret service SVR RF, but mostly in the form of influencing, with the aim to promote Russian interests through the AEMN.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Kovács was sentenced to one and a half years imprisonment for fraud and falsification of documents to the detriment of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The party did not apply for registration with the newly established Authority for European Political Parties and European Political Foundations (APPF), which was required from 2017, in good time.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] An application by the party foundation ITE was rejected by the APPF, as the AEMN was not registered itself at that time.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Subsequently, the AEMN's application for funding for 2018 was rejected accordingly.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] Finally, the AEMN was registered as a European political party on 12 January 2018.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] At the end of 2018, the AENM was removed from the register again.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] The background was a change in the registration rules, according to which European parties had to submit member parties (with parliamentarians) from seven EU member states in the register.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] This put an end to the previous practice of AENM registering individual parliamentarians from national parties who did not belong to AENM but to other European parties.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For example, parliamentarians from the Front National had regularly provided signatures for the AENM, the APF and the MENL – to which the FN belongs.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For the 2019 European Parliament election, AEMN chairman Kovacs provided the necessary signature of support for the candidacy of the Italian party CasaPound Italia.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] None of the parties in the AEMN's environment was able to win mandates in the election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] After the election, the party was no longer active.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] For the 2024 European Parliament election in Italy, Royal Italy submitted a symbol with the text "Alleanza europea dei movimenti nazionali" at the top.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-european-national-movements] In 2022, Royal Italy ran with United Right who made a deal with CasaPound in 2019.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] The **Alliance of Independent Democrats in Europe** (AIDE) (**Alliance des Démocrates Indépendants en Europe** (ADIE) in French) was a Eurosceptic, nationalist European political party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE was created on 28 October 2005 in the Rhône prefecture.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE described itself as the centre-right faction of the eurosceptic IND/DEM group, with the EUDemocrats, the United Kingdom Independence Party and the European Christian Political Movement comprising the other factions of that group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] As of January 2007, the group operated a limited French-language website.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] The group's website implied the existence of British, Czech, French, Greek, Irish, Italian and Polish delegations and identified Movement for France (MpF) MEP Patrick Louis as the president of AIDE.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-independent-democrats-in-europe] AIDE was dissolved with effect from 31 December 2008 and was defunded in the February 2009 meeting of the Bureau of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The Mission of the ALDE-PACE group is to promote core values of the Council of Europe: democracy, human rights and the rule of law through enhanced political actions inside and outside the Parliamentary Assembly of the Council of Europe.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] ALDE adopted a new mission statement 22 January 2018 outlining the values and objectives of the group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] ALDE members realize these objectives by actively participating in the Parliamentary Assembly sessions, working in its Committees, drafting reports, initiating debates and ensuring the follow-up of this work in their home countries.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Outside the Assembly the group members are committed to promoting the principles of the Council of Europe and giving support to liberal and democratic values throughout Europe.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] According to the Rules of Procedure of the ALDE-PACE (as amended on 22 January 2018), the Bureau of the Group consists of the Chairperson, 11 Vice-Chairpersons and the Treasurer of the Group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Chairpersons of committees and former Chairpersons of the Group are ex officio members of the Bureau.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The permanent secretariat of the Group is located in the headquarters of the Council of Europe in Strasbourg, France (Palais de l’Europe).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The secretariat is chaired by Dr Maria Bigday.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] It was not until after the celebration of the Council of Europe's 25th anniversary in 1964 that the Rules of Procedure of the Consultative Assembly (its name was not changed to Parliamentary Assembly until 1974) discreetly mentioned that members had the possibility of forming political groups.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The history of the liberal group in the PACE dates back to the early 1970s (first documented in 1974).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] At the time it was called the Liberal Group and consisted of 30 members headed by Frederik Portheine (Netherlands).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] In the mid-80s the group changed its name to the "Liberal, Democratic and Reformers' Group" (LDR) in order to make the Group's political ideals universally and unequivocally recognisable.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The name "Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe" (ALDE) was adopted on 20 June 2005 in order to enhance cooperation with other European liberal and democratic bodies, in particular the ALDE of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Daniel Tarschys (Sweden) was Secretary General of the Council of Europe from 1994 - 1999.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The permanent secretariat of the Group operates since 1978, when Mr Peter Kallenberger was appointed Secretary of the Group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] After he retired in 2010, Ms Maria Bigday took up the position of the Secretary.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The ALDE-PACE Group regularly holds conferences, hearings, seminars and round tables in the framework of the Council of Europe scope of interest.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] It also co-organises joint events with other European and international liberal and democratic institutions.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] Information relating to these side events is found on the ALDE-PACE Pace website and in the ALDE newsletter published after each session.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-in-the-parliamentary-assembly-of-t] The ALDE-PACE holds stable partnership with major European and world liberal and democratic organisations.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The **Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party** (**ALDE Party**) is a liberal European political party composed of national parties from across Europe, mainly active in the European Union.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The ALDE Party is affiliated with Liberal International and a recognised European political party, incorporated as a non-profit association under Belgian law.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] It was founded on 26 March 1976 in Stuttgart as a confederation of national political parties under the name "Federation of Liberal and Democrat Parties in Europe" and renamed "European Liberals and Democrats" (ELD) in 1977 and "European Liberal Democrats and Reformists" (ELDR) in 1986.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 30 April 2004, the ELDR was reformed as an official European party, the "European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party" (ELDR Party).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Prior to the 2004 European election, the European party had been represented through its own group, the European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party Group (ELDR) Group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In June 2019, the ALDE group was succeeded by Renew Europe.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of 2024, ALDE Party is represented in European Union institutions, with 51 MEPs and five members of the European Commission.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Of the 27 EU member states, there are two with ALDE-affiliated Prime Ministers: Kristen Michal (Estonian Reform Party) in Estonia and Alexander De Croo (Open VLD) in Belgium.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE Party members are also in governments in ten other EU member states: Cyprus, France, Denmark, Finland, Sweden, Ireland, Luxembourg, Lithuania, Germany and the Netherlands.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Charles Michel, former Belgian prime minister, was the president of the European Council until December 2024.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE's think tank is the European Liberal Forum, led by Jan-Christoph Oetjen MEP, and gathers 46 member organisations.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The youth wing of ALDE is the European Liberal Youth (LYMEC), which is predominantly based upon youth and student liberal organisations but contains also a small number of individual members.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 2011, ALDE Party became the first pan-European party to create the status of individual membership.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Since then, between 1000 and close to 3000 members (the numbers fluctuate annually) maintained direct membership in the ALDE Party from several EU countries.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Over 40 coordinators mobilised liberal ideas, initiatives and expertise across the continent under the leadership of the steering committee, which was first chaired by Julie Cantalou.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The ALDE Party took a step further in the direction of becoming a truly pan-European party when granting voting rights to individual members' delegates at the Party Congress.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Individual membership was eventually discontinued in 2023.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 2025, the Alliance was declared an undesirable organization in Russia.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Pan-European liberalism has a long history dating back to the foundation of Liberal International in April 1947.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 26 March 1976, the Federation of Liberal and Democrat Parties in Europe was established in Stuttgart.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] The founding parties of the federation were the Free Democratic Party of Germany, Radical Party of France, Venstre of Denmark, Italian Liberal Party, Dutch People's Party for Freedom and Democracy and Democratic Party of Luxembourg.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Observer members joining later in 1976 were the Danish Social Liberal Party, French Radical Party of the Left and Independent Republicans, British Liberal Party, and Italian Republican Party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In 1977, the federation was renamed European Liberals and Democrats, in 1986, European Liberal Democrats and Reformists.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 10 November 2012, the ELDR Party adopted the name of the alliance between the two parties, to match the parliamentary group and the alliance.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] On 12 June 2019, the ALDE group was succeeded by a new enlarged group, Renew Europe, which primarily consists of ALDE and EDP member parties and France's La République En Marche!
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As a registered European political party, ALDE is entitled to European public funding, which it has received continuously since 2004.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of European public funding received by ALDE.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] In line with the Regulation on European political parties and European political foundations, ALDE also raises private funds to co-finance its activities.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of 2025, European parties must raise at least 10% of their reimbursable expenditure from private sources, while the rest can be covered using European public funding.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of contributions and donations received by the ALDE.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As of January 2026 ALDE party had 55 full member and ten affiliated parties from EU and non-EU countries.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Only delegates from full members of the ALDE Party and its youth wing LYMEC, together with the delegates of the ALDE Party Supporters and ALDE Party Bureau members, are permitted to vote at the ALDE Congress and Council.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Affiliated member parties have non-voting delegates.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] ALDE also includes a number of individual members.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] For many years, ALDE had the largest number of individual members of all European parties; however, this membership was discontinued with only one individual member remaining as of 2024.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] As most other European parties, it has not sought to develop mass individual membership.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alliance-of-liberals-and-democrats-for-europe-party] Below is the evolution of individual membership of ALDE since 2019.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Its name reflects its resistance to the mainstream policies of Angela Merkel and her slogan *Alternativlosigkeit* (lit.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] 'alternative-less-ness', a German version of "there is no alternative").
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Established in April 2013, AfD narrowly missed the 5% electoral threshold to sit in the Bundestag during the 2013 federal election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party won seven seats in the 2014 European Parliament election in Germany as a member of the European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2021 federal election, AfD dropped to being the fifth-largest party in the 20th Bundestag.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Following the 2025 federal election, it became the second-largest party and the largest opposition party in the 21st Bundestag.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD was founded by Gauland, Bernd Lucke, and former members of the Christian Democratic Union of Germany (CDU) to oppose the policies of the eurozone as a right-wing and moderately Eurosceptic alternative to the centre-right but pro-European CDU.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party presented itself as an economically liberal, Eurosceptic, and conservative movement in its early years.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD subsequently moved further to the right, and expanded its policies under successive leaderships to include opposition to immigration, Islam, and the European Union.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Since 2015, with the beginning of the refugee crisis in Europe, AfD's ideology has been characterised by German nationalism, *völkisch* nationalism (ethno-nationalism), right-wing populism, and national conservatism.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] It has a policy focus on opposing Islam, opposing immigration into Germany, especially Muslim immigration into Germany, welfare chauvinism, Euroscepticism, denial of human-caused global warming, and supporting closer relations with Russia.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] They have been observed by various state offices for the protection of the constitution since 2018.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD's leadership has denied that the party is racist and has been internally divided on whether to endorse such groups.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In January 2022, after a failed power struggle, party leader Jörg Meuthen resigned his party chairmanship with immediate effect and left AfD, stating that the party had moved far to the right with totalitarian traits and in large parts was no longer based on Germany's liberal democratic basic order.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Lucke had left the party in 2015 with a similar view.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In 2023, the Young Alternative for Germany was officially categorized by the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution (BfV) as a confirmed extremist organisation.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In 2025, the BfV officially classified AfD as a "confirmed right-wing extremist endeavor", which allows authorities to increase surveillance, and permits the use of informants and monitoring of communications, though this classification was suspended following a 2026 court injunction.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2021 federal elections, AfD fell from third to fifth place overall but made gains in the eastern states.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the former East Berlin, it came in second after SPD with 20.5% of the vote; in the west, it came in fifth with 8.4% of the vote.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2025 German federal election, AfD received a record 20.8% of the vote and ended in second place behind CDU/CSU.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Their manifesto was endorsed by several economists, journalists, and business leaders, and stated that the eurozone had proven to be "unsuitable" as a currency area and that southern European states were "sinking into poverty under the competitive pressure of the euro".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Some candidates of what would become AfD sought election in Lower Saxony as part of the *Electoral Alternative 2013* in alliance with the Free Voters, an association participating in local elections without specific federal or foreign policies, and received 1% of the vote.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In February 2013, the group decided to found a new party to compete in the 2013 federal election; according to a leaked email from Lucke, the Free Voters leadership declined to join forces.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party was founded on 6 February 2013.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 14 April 2013, the AfD announced its presence to the wider public when it held its first convention in Berlin, elected the party leadership, and adopted a party platform.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Bernd Lucke, the entrepreneur Frauke Petry and Konrad Adam were elected as speakers.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD's federal board also chose Alexander Gauland, Roland Klaus, and Patricia Casale as its three deputy speakers.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party elected the treasurer Norbert Stenzel and the three assessors Irina Smirnova, Beatrix Diefenbach, and Wolf-Joachim Schünemann.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The economist Joachim Starbatty, along with Jörn Kruse, Helga Luckenbach, Dirk Meyer, and Roland Vaubel, were elected to the party's scientific advisory board.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Between 31 March and 12 May 2013 AfD founded affiliates in all 16 states of Germany in order to participate in the federal elections.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 15 June 2013 the Young Alternative for Germany was founded in Darmstadt as the AfD's youth organisation.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] During the British prime minister David Cameron's visit to Germany in April 2013, the British Conservative Party was reported to have contacted both AfD and the Free Voters to discuss possible cooperation, supported by the European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR) group of the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In June 2013 Bernd Lucke gave a question and answer session organized by the Conservative Party-allied Bruges Group think tank in Portcullis House, London.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In a detailed report in the conservative *Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung* in April 2013, the paper's Berlin-based political correspondent Majid Sattar revealed that the Social Democratic Party of Germany (SPD) and CDU had conducted opposition research to blunt the growth and attraction of AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Advocating the abolition of the euro, AfD took a more radical stance than the Free Voters.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The Pirate Party Germany opposed any coalition with AfD at their 2013 spring convention.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD did not regard itself as a splinter party from the CDU, as its early membership also contained a former state leader from the Free Democratic Party and members of the Federation of Independent Voters, a pressure group of independents and small business owners.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 22 September 2013 AfD won 4.7% of the votes in the 2013 federal election, just missing the 5% barrier to enter the Bundestag.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party won about 2 million party list votes and 810,000 constituency votes, which was 1.9% of the total of these votes cast across Germany.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD did not participate in the 2013 Bavaria state election held on 15 September.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party gained parliamentary representation for the first time in the state parliament of Hesse, with the defection of Jochen Paulus from the Free Democratic Party to AfD in early May 2013; he was not re-elected and left office in January 2014.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2013 Hesse state election held on 22 September, the same day as the 2013 federal election, AfD failed to gain representation with just 4% of the vote.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In early 2014, the Federal Constitutional Court of Germany ruled the proposed 3% vote hurdle for representation in the European elections unconstitutional, and the 2014 European Parliament election became the first run in Germany without a barrier for representation.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD held a party conference on 25 January 2014 in Aschaffenburg, northwest Bavaria.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The conference chose the slogan *Mut zu Deutschland* ("Courage [to stand up] for Germany") to replace the former slogan *Mut zur Wahrheit* (lit.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] 'Courage [to speak] the truth', or more succinctly, "Telling it as it is"), which prompted disagreement among the federal board that the party could be seen as too anti-European.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] A compromise was reached by using the slogan "MUT ZU D*EU*TSCHLAND", with the "EU" in "DEUTSCHLAND" encircled by the 12 stars of the European flag.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The conference elected the top six candidates for the European elections on 26 January 2014 and met again the following weekend to choose the remaining euro candidates.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Candidates from 7th–28th place on the party list were selected in Berlin on 1 February.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Party chairman Bernd Lucke was elected as lead candidate.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In February 2014, AfD officials said they had discussed alliances with the British anti-EU UK Independence Party (UKIP), which Lucke and the federal board of AfD opposed, and also with the European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR) group, to which Britain's Conservative Party belongs.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In April 2014 Hans-Olaf Henkel, AfD's second candidate on the European election list, ruled out forming a group with UKIP. stating that he saw the Conservatives as the preferred partner in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 10 May 2014 Lucke had been in talks with the Czech and Polish member parties of the ECR group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2014 European Parliament election on 25 May, AfD came in fifth place in Germany, with 7.1% of the national vote (2,065,162 votes), and seven Members of the European parliament (MEPs).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 12 June 2014, it was announced that AfD had been accepted into the ECR group in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The official vote result was not released to the public, but figures of 29 votes for and 26 against were reported by the membership.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The inclusion of AfD in the ECR group was said to have caused mild tensions between the German chancellor Angela Merkel and the British prime minister David Cameron.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 31 August AfD received 9.7% of the vote in the 2014 Saxony state election, winning 14 seats in the Landtag of Saxony.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 14 September, AfD obtained 10.6% of the vote in the 2014 Thuringian and 12.2% in the Brandenburg state election, winning 11 seats in both state parliaments.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 15 February 2015 AfD won 6.1% of the vote in the Hamburg state election, gaining the mandate for eight seats in the Hamburg Parliament, winning their first seats in a western German state.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 10 May 2015, AfD secured in the 5.5% of the vote in the 2015 Bremen state election gaining representation in their fifth state parliament on a 50% turnout.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] After months of factional infighting and a cancelled party gathering in June 2015, Frauke Petry was elected on 4 July 2015 as the *de facto* principal speaker of the party with 60% of the member votes ahead of Bernd Lucke at a party congress in Essen.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Petry was a member of the national-conservative faction of AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Her leadership was widely seen as heralding a shift of the party to the right to focus more on issues such as immigration, Islam, and strengthening ties to Russia, a shift which was claimed by Lucke as turning the party into a "Pegida party".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the following week, five MEPs exited the party on 7 July, the only remaining MEPs being Beatrix von Storch and Marcus Pretzell, and Lucke announced on 8 July 2015 that he was resigning from AfD, citing the rise of xenophobic and pro-Russian sentiments in the party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] At a meeting of members of the Wake-up call (Weckruf 2015) group on 19 July 2015, AfD founder Bernd Lucke and former AfD members announced they would form a new party, the Alliance for Progress and Renewal, under the founding principles of AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The split off party was eventually renamed the Liberal Conservative Reformers, but had little electoral success.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In February 2016 AfD announced a cooperation pact with the Freedom Party of Austria (FPÖ).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 8 March 2016, the bureau of the ECR group began motions to exclude AfD from their group due to its links with the far-right FPÖ, inviting the two remaining AfD MEPs to leave the group by 31 March, with a motion of exclusion to be tabled on 12 April if they refuse to leave voluntarily.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] While von Storch left the ECR group on 8 April to join the Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy group, Pretzell let himself be expelled on 12 April.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] With the European migrant crisis remaining the dominant national issue, elections on 13 March were held in the three states of Baden-Württemberg, Rhineland-Palatinate, and Saxony-Anhalt, and saw the AfD receiving double-digit percentages of the vote in all three states.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2016 Saxony-Anhalt state election, AfD reached second place in the Landtag, receiving 24.2% of the vote.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2016 Baden-Württemberg state election, AfD achieved third place, with 15.1% of the vote.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2016 Rhineland-Palatinate state election, AfD again reached third place, with 12.6% of the vote.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In Angela Merkel's home state of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, her CDU was beaten into third place following a strong showing of AfD, who contested at state level for the first time, to claim the second-highest polling with 20.8% of the vote in the 2016 state election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Rising support for AfD meant that The Greens and the NDP failed to reach the 5% threshold to qualify for seats in the Landtag of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, and consequently lost their seats.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2016 Berlin state election, which AfD also contested for the first time, the party achieved a vote of 14.2%, making them the fifth largest party represented in the state assembly.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Their vote seems to have come equally from the SPD and CDU, whose votes declined 6.7% and 5.7%, respectively.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] At the party congress held on 30 April to 1 May 2016, AfD adopted a policy platform based upon opposition to Islam, calling for the ban of Islamic symbols including burqas, minarets, and *adhan* (call to prayer), using the slogan "Islam is not a part of Germany".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] At the party conference in April 2017, Frauke Petry announced that she would not run as the party's main candidate for the 2017 federal election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] This announcement grew out of internal power struggle as the party's support had fallen in polls from 15% in the summer of 2016 to 7% just before the conference.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Björn Höcke from the far-right wing of the party and Petry were attempting to push each other out of the party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Petry's decision was partly seen as a step to avoid a vote at the conference on the issue of her standing.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party chose Alexander Gauland, a stark conservative who worked as an editor and was a former member of the CDU, to lead the party in the elections.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Gauland supported the retention of Höcke's party membership.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Alice Weidel, who is perceived as more moderate and neoliberal, was elected as his running mate.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2017 federal election AfD won 12.6% of the vote and received 94 seats; this was the first time it had won seats in the Bundestag.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] It won three constituency seats, which would have been enough to qualify for proportionally-elected seats in any event.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Under a long-standing law intended to benefit regional parties, any party that wins at least three constituency seats qualifies for its share of proportionally-elected seats, regardless of vote share.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] She also said that she would be leaving the party at some future date.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Petry formed the Blue Party in September 2017.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Four members of AfD in the Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania legislature, including Bernhard Wild, also left the party to form Citizens for Mecklenburg-Vorpommern, which folded in December 2018.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 6 November 2019 Petry announced that the Blue Party would dissolve by the end of the year.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In 2018 André Poggenburg, AfD's regional leader of the eastern Saxony-Anhalt state, resigned his post after making racist remarks concerning Turks and immigrants with dual citizenship.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In 2019, Poggenburg started a new far-right party, *Aufbruch deutscher Patrioten – Mitteldeutschland* (ADPM), which he left in August 2019 after his internal call to dissolve ADPM and to support AfD in the upcoming state elections of fall 2019 was denied.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Ahead of the 2021 federal election, AfD campaigned with the slogan "Germany.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] But Normal" and took a position of opposing further lockdowns in response to the COVID-19 pandemic in Germany.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Having moved further right on economic issues and remaining strongly right on socio-cultural issues, despite attempts to normalize, AfD's manifesto for the federal election was deemed to be still too radical for the party to take part in government.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the federal election, AfD saw a dip in national vote share by getting 10.3% of the vote, compared to 12.6% in 2017; however, the party emerged as the largest in the states of Saxony and Thuringia, and saw a strong performance in eastern Germany.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party's results drew a mixed analysis from AfD members and political commentators, the latter of whom attributed the slight decline to visible infighting, whereas AfD candidates such as Alice Weidel blamed media bias against the party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The political scientist Kai Arzheimer commented that the result "wasn't any appreciable increase, but it wasn't a disaster for them." Arzheimer also posited that the result demonstrated that AfD had firmly established itself in German national politics but had not reached beyond its core support.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD's top candidates Tino Chrupalla and Weidel praised the result as "solid", while party spokesman Jörg Meuthen stated that the party should reevaluate the result and aim on "sending strong signals towards the center" to win back new voters.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD held their three seats in the 2022 Saarland state election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] At the same time, they lost all their seats in the 2022 Schleswig-Holstein state election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2022 Lower Saxony state election in October, AfD won 9 more seats compared to 2017 to a total of 18.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2023 Berlin repeat state election AfD recorded a small upswing by gaining 4 seats compared to the 2021 election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2023 Bremen state election AfD did not participate and lost all their seats, as the Bremen electoral committee had barred AfD from the election due to internal divisions that had resulted in them submitting two lists of candidates.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The Citizens in Rage, another right-wing party, participated instead; they received 10 seats (after having only one seat in 2019) in Bremen's state parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 25 June 2023, amidst rises in polls, Thuringia's AfD won its first district election in Sonneberg.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the run-off election held on 2 July, the AfD candidate Hannes Loth won against the independent politician Nils Naumann, becoming AfD's first ever mayor.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 8 October state elections, AfD significantly increased its share in Hesse where it became the second-biggest party (+9 seats) and in Bavaria, where it became the third (+10 seats).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Observers considered the increase of support for the AfD as not being limited to the local level.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Opinion polling for the 2025 German federal election conducted in early July 2023 showed that the AfD polled more than the SPD, achieving second place behind the CDU/CSU alliance.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The SPD co-leader said a ban should be considered if the AfD is categorized as a group of "proven Right-wing extremists" by the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Friedrich Merz, the CDU leader, warned that "banning parties has never actually solved political problems".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Germans are evenly split on a ban, with 47 per cent in favour and 47 per cent against; the ban is more popular in the west and among liberal Greens.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In December 2023 Tim Lochner of AfD was elected Mayor of Pirna (Saxony).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] He became the first mayor of a city with more than 20,000 inhabitants to be a member of the party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In 2023, the AfD saw 86 violent attacks on AfD party representatives.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] This was more than on any other German party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In January 2024 Correctiv reported that members of AfD had secretly met with figures from the German and Austrian far-right in November 2023, in which they allegedly discussed a "remigration" plan for deporting immigrants, which could include naturalised German citizens.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Those present included the Identitarian activist Martin Sellner.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The AfD distanced itself from the meeting, saying it was not responsible for what was discussed and that its members had attended only in a personal capacity.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Alice Weidel parted ways with Roland Hartwig, an advisor who was present at the meeting.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The plan was condemned by German politicians, including Chancellor Olaf Scholz.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The report sparked protests against the AfD across Germany, with protestors calling for a ban of AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Subsequently, the AfD member Maximilian Krah got involved in controversy, prompting AfD to be expelled from the ID group, with EKRE supporting expulsion of Krah, but opposing the removal of the entire AfD delegation, and the FPÖ opposing the expulsion of AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 9 June 2024 AfD won 16% of the vote in the European Parliament elections, second only to the CDU/CSU and almost five percentage points more than in the 2019 election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD prevailed in all five former East German states.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] One of the party's leaders, Tino Chrupalla, hailed the results as "historic".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In an attempt to rejoin the ID group, the AfD replaced its controversial candidate Maximilian Krah with René Aust as head of the AfD delegation in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] However, AfD failed to join ID, or now named Patriots for Europe.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Instead, AfD formed the new ESN group which was composed predominantly of AfD members, as well as some other ethnonationalist parties across Europe.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the 2024 Thuringian state election, the AfD became the first far-right party in Germany since the Nazi Party to win a plurality of seats in a state election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The AfD also performed strongly in Brandenburg and Saxony.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 23 February 2025 AfD won 20.8% of the vote in the German federal election, second to the CDU/CSU.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] It gained 10.4 percentage points over the 2021 election result.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The party won nearly a third of the votes in each of the East German states, the lowest being 32.5% in Brandenburg and the highest 38.5% in Thuringia, and won all but three constituency seats in the former East Germany (Potsdam, Erfurt and one of two seats in Leipzig).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In the former West Germany, the party beat the SPD for second place by less than 0.5% of the vote and received more than 20% of the vote in two southwestern states: Saarland (21.6%) and Rhineland-Palatinate (20.1%).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In April 2025, for the first time in German history, AfD was ahead of the CDU/CSU (Union) in some opinion polls for the next federal election, while other polls put it on par with the Union or in second place.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Support for the CDU/CSU, an alliance that won the election, fell from 29% to 24%, while AfD rose by three percentage points from 22% to 25%, partially becoming the most popular party in Germany.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In May 2025 the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution (BfV) classified AfD as a "confirmed right-wing extremist endeavor".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In a 1,100-page classified and undisclosed report, BfV experts found that AfD is a "racist and anti-Muslim organisation".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The classification will allow German authorities to monitor AfD and possibly limit or halt public funding for it.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] It may also inspire its opponents to attempt to get it banned.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] AfD leaders Alice Weidel and Tino Chrupalla said the decision was "clearly politically motivated" and was a "severe blow to German democracy".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] They argued that AfD is being discredited and persecuted by the government.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Chancellor Olaf Scholz said that BfV provided a "very detailed justification" for its decision and that proceedings to ban the AfD must not be rushed.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Several federal states in Germany have begun considering measures that would ban AfD members from being employed in jobs like civil servants, police officers, teachers or soldiers in response to the classification.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On 4 May 2025 a poll conducted by Insa Polling Institute which surveyed 1,001 people found that 48% of them favour banning AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The poll also showed that 61% of participants consider AfD a "right-wing extremist” party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] A court in Cologne will start reviewing the case once BfV confirms that it has been notified of the lawsuit.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] Sieghard Knodel, a member of AfD in the Bundestag, announced his resignation from the party on 6 May 2025.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] He wrote in an email: "In light of the classification of the party as confirmed right-wing extremist by the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution, I must protect my private and business environment".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] He said that he would continue to serve as a non-attached member of parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] On May 8, the extremist classification of AfD was temporarily suspended by the BfV pending an official court judgement.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The AfD's leaders said that the decision was a "first important step" that would help "counter the accusation of right-wing extremism".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] The report by the BfV that led to the classification was later leaked to the public.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p01] In August, five direct and two reserve AfD candidates died within 14 days of each other ahead of local elections in North Rhine-Westphalia.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD is broadly considered to be a right-wing and national-conservative movement in both socioeconomic and sociocultural terms.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Other commentators have categorized it as a radical right populist party or as "a typical radical right-wing populist party", with an emphasis on nativism.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Within its elected representation and grassroots membership, AfD has grown to contain interparty factions that range from more moderate conservatives to radicals.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] At that time, the party also advocated support for Swiss-style semi-direct democracy, major reforms to the eurozone, opposition to immigration, and opposed same-sex marriage.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] During this period, the party espoused economic liberal, ordoliberal, and national liberal policy stances.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Former party MEP Hans-Olaf Henkel likened AfD's early platform to the Conservative Party in Britain rather than hard Eurosceptic or nationalist parties such as the UK Independence Party or the National Front in France.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD was also compared to the Tea Party movement by some media outlets due to its campaigns against eurozone bailouts, although AfD's early leadership disputed this and said it was not looking to attract right-wing extremists into the party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2015 more moderate members, including its founder and former chairman Bernd Lucke, left AfD after Frauke Petry was elected chairperson to found a new party, the Alliance for Progress and Renewal, which was renamed the Liberal Conservative Reformers in November 2016.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD underwent a further shift to the right after Petry left the party in 2017 and formed The Blue Party, following AfD's adoption of more hardline Islamophobic, anti-immigration positions, and historical revisionist remarks by leading AfD figures.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party now resembles other populist radical right parties in Europe but is somewhat unusual because it maintains visible ties to even more extreme groups.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party has been described by political scientists as more radical than many other European right-wing populist parties, including the Sweden Democrats, the Danish People's Party, and the Freedom Party of Austria.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has been described as, and accused of, containing members sympathetic to the Identitarian movement and Pegida.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD leadership has been split on whether to embrace these movements within the party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In early March 2021 most of Germany's major media outlets reported that the *Bundesverfassungsschutz* had placed the whole AfD under surveillance as a "suspected extremist group".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In response to claims from AfD members that the move was intended to damage the party's chances in the 2021 German federal election, the agency stated it would not make public announcements regarding investigations into AfD or its candidates for the foreseeable future.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] After the revelations, the surveillance was blocked by the courts to give equal opportunities among political parties in a key election year.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2022 it was ruled that the BfV may classify and monitor the entire party as a suspected right-wing extremist group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] A corresponding lawsuit by AfD was dismissed because "there were sufficient factual indications of anti-constitutional efforts within the AfD".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] On 26 April 2023 the BfV, after four years of investigations into the Young Alternative for Germany, categorized that group as a confirmed extremist organisation.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] This allowed the chief of the BfV Thomas Haldenwang to place the youth wing under even more intensive surveillance than the tapping of phone and the use of undercover agents that had been the case until then.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2025, the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution officially classified AfD as a "confirmed right-wing extremist endeavor," which allows authorities to increase surveillance, and permits the use of informants and monitoring of communications.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The expertise by the BfV, that led to that classification, was later leaked to the public.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD is anti-communist and engaged in red-baiting by comparing Angela Merkel and her government to the secret police in East Germany.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Some academics have described additional factions representing economic liberals or the Christian right.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The political author Jeffrey Gedmin has described the present incarnation of AfD as somewhat lacking in a consistent ideological vision and containing a broad church of members who are conservatives, social conservatives, radical-rightists, and others who do not present clear ideological narrative.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] He also described some of its core voter support as ranging from far-right nationalists to moderate but traditionalist and disaffected conservatives.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Over time a focus on German nationalism, on reclaiming Germany's sovereignty and national pride, especially in repudiation of Germany's culture of shame with regard to its Nazi past, became more central in AfD's ideology and a central plank in its populist appeals.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Petry, who led the moderate wing of the party, said that Germany should reclaim *völkisch* from its Nazi connotations, while the more right-wing Björn Höcke regularly speaks of the *Vaterland* ("fatherland") and *Volk* ("nation" or "people", but with a strong ethnic or racial connotation).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In January 2017 Höcke in a speech stated, in reference to the Berlin Holocaust Memorial, that "Germans are the only people in the world who plant a monument of shame in the heart of the capital" and criticised this "laughable policy of coming to terms with the past".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Höcke continued that Germany should make a "180 degree" turn with regard to its sense of national pride.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Some AfD members and candidates have expressed antisemitic attitudes.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD leaders have repeatedly denied accusations of antisemitism.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] According to a study conducted by the Forsa Institute in 2019, while 2% of the German population agreed with the statement that "the Holocaust is propaganda of the Allied Powers", that proportion was 15% among AfD supporters.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The propaganda steamroller is getting stronger rather than weaker over the years, and in more and more countries the Jewish 'truth' about the Holocaust is being given legal protection.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2017, ten AfD Bundestag members were found to have participated in a closed Facebook group named "the Patriots" in which, among other things, antisemitic, racist, pro-Nazi and conspiratorial posts were widespread.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] One meme posted therein, which showed the Holocaust victim Anne Frank's face edited on a pizza box labelled with the German equivalent of "fresh from the oven", gained particular media attention.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2023 Felix Klein, the Federal Government Commissioner for Jewish Life in Germany and the Fight against antisemitism, stated that leading forces within AfD relativize the Holocaust and that the party condones antisemitism.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Josef Schuster, President of the Central Council of Jews in Germany, stated in 2024 that he is "concerned that the AfD would deliberately act against Jewish life, if it fits into their concept", and that the party offers antisemites a home.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] A study commissioned by the American Jewish Committee in 2021 came to the conclusion that antisemitism belongs to the "programmatic core" of the AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] According to the study, the party conducts "targeted campaigns" against Jewish celebrities.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The study's author, Lars Rensmann, stated that "despite some lip service to the contrary, hostility towards Israel, Holocaust relativization, antisemitic conspiracy thinking and anti-Jewish images occupy a prominent place" in AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD supports a ban on kosher slaughter within the country, as well as the "import and sale of kosher meat".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD instead wants to require the stunning of animals before slaughter which is against both Jewish and Muslim religious law that both require animals to be conscious when their necks are cut.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD describes German national identity as under threat both from European integration and from the presence and accommodation of immigrants and refugees within Germany.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Former leader Petry said in March 2016: "I'm not against immigration, but ... the economic and social consequences of migration on both home and host countries are equally momentous ....
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The immigration of so many Muslims will change our culture.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] If this change is desired, it must be the product of a democratic decision supported by a broad majority.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In its programme, AfD wants to end what it describes as mass immigration and focus on taking in small numbers of skilled immigrants who are expected to integrate into society and speak German.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] It encourages German nationals to have more children, as opposed to trying to boost the German population through foreign migration.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party wants to review EU freedom of movement rules and states that immigrants must be employed and contribute to social security through paying taxes for at least four years before being allowed to receive state benefits.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD calls for mass deportations of foreign born criminals with multiple citizenship or permanent residency.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party describes the Geneva Convention on Refugees as "outdated", calls for stricter vetting of refugees, and believes the German government should invest in special economic and safe zones in third world nations as opposed to taking in large numbers of asylum seekers without background checks.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD is critical of multiculturalism in Germany.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party favours banning the burqa, the Islamic call to prayer in public areas and the construction of new minarets, ending foreign funding of mosques and putting imams through a state vetting procedure.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD began to employ anti-Muslim rhetoric during the leadership of Petry, who responded positively to comparisons between the party and Pegida.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2016 the party adopted several anti-Muslim positions and stated in its manifesto that "Islam does not belong to Germany.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In January 2025 the Karlsruhe branch of the AfD initiated a controversial campaign by distributing flyers resembling flight tickets labeled *"Abschiebetickets"* ("deportation tickets") in mailboxes.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] These flyers included a QR code linking to AfD Karlsruhe's website and were intended as promotional material for the upcoming Bundestag elections.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The action prompted investigations by the criminal police on suspicions of incitement to hatred (*Volksverhetzung*).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In January 2025, after a deadly knife attack perpetrated by an Afghan migrant, who had no residence permit, the CDU issued a motion regarding migration into the federal parliament, which attained a majority due to the AfD voting alongside the CDU.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] With this motion, CDU leader Friedrich Merz ignored his own proposal, uttered in November 2024, to only put questions to the vote that would find a majority without the AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The Bundestag went on to reject the CDU's proposed legislation a few days later, largely due to a dozen CDU legislators abstaining, a decision seen to be sparked by the AfD-related controversy.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] According to its interim electoral manifesto, AfD opposes same-sex marriage and favours civil unions.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD deputy leader Beatrix von Storch has publicly opposed same-sex marriage.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In an effort to overturn same-sex marriage laws, AfD filed a lawsuit over the issue in 2017.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Hans-Christoph Berndt, the AfD's lead candidate for the 2024 Brandenburg state election, announced that, if elected, he would ban the practice of displaying rainbow flags on public buildings in the state.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD parliamentary group of the Landtag of Lower Saxony also introduced a motion to ban rainbow flags from public buildings in 2024.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD supports a ban on circumcision for non-medical reasons for those under the age of majority, saying that the practice constituted "serious violations of fundamental rights".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Alternative for Germany is an anti-abortion party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD has described its position as "pro-life" and rejects any state support for abortion.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The left-leaning newspaper *Die Tageszeitung* described the party as advocating "old gender roles".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Wolfgang Gedeon, an elected AfD representative, has included feminism, along with "sexualism" and "migrationism", in an ideology he calls "green communism" that he opposes, and argues for family values as part of German identity.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] As AfD has campaigned for traditional roles for women, it has aligned itself with groups opposed to modern feminism.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The youth wing of the party has used social media to campaign against aspects of modern feminism, with the support of party leadership.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Despite the 2015 split of economic liberals, AfD can still be broadly characterized as neoliberal on economic terms, emphasizing deregulation and much limited state intervention.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Attempts by some party factions to emphasize small and medium-sized enterprises, and advocate protectionism over free trade, have not had much success.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has a platform of climate change denial.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD accepts that the climate is changing, however, it denies that this change is attributable to human influences.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Instead the party argues that climate change is entirely caused by natural factors.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD argues that the rising carbon dioxide concentrations have been beneficial (contributed to a "greening" of Earth).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Next to its climate change denial, AfD opposes far-reaching climate policies: The party opposes energy transformation policies (*Energiewende*), wants to scrap the German Renewable Energy Act, the German Energy Saving Regulations, and the German Renewable Energy Heat Act.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] They also want to end bioenergy subsidies and restrict "uncontrolled expansion of wind energy".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party rejects the European Green Deal and has warned against the deindustrialization of Europe.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party argues that the energy transition threatens energy security, possibly leading to energy blackouts.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] It, therefore, views lignite as the only native energy source that can guarantee German energy security and energy self-sufficiency.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Furthermore, AfD wants to reinstate Germany's nuclear plants, arguing that closures between 2002 and 2011 were "economically damaging and not objectively justified".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party argues that the government should "allow a lifetime extension of still operating nuclear power plants on a transitional basis".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD wants a reinstatement of conscription in Germany, starting for able-bodied men at the age of 18.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] While AfD had been pro-NATO and pro-United States during the first Trump administration, it had been sharply critical of the Biden administration.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] It was significantly divided on whether to support Russia, but has since moved to a pro-Russian direction, opposing sanctions on Russia supported by NATO and the United States and calling for an end to military aid to Ukraine.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] It is also divided on free-trade agreements.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In March 2019, party leader Alexander Gauland said in an interview with the Russian newspaper *Komsomolskaya Pravda* that they consider the war in Donbas to be a Ukrainian internal matter, and that Germany should not get involved in the internal affairs of Ukraine or Russia.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] He also said AfD is against international sanctions on Russia.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD members have called for a more independent stance from the United States.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party has also endorsed accusations that the United States was involved in the 2022 Nord Stream pipeline sabotage, although by 2026 after investigations they had called for compensation from Ukraine, despite historical denials of involvement by Ukrainian President Zelenskyy.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has also called NATO's anti-Russian stance overly ideological and detrimental to Germany's interests.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] A large number of AfD delegates boycotted Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy in June 2024 when he gave a speech to the Bundestag.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In February 2025, some high-ranking AfD members criticised Chrupalla's pro-Moscow position on foreign policy.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] These include organizing street protests against NATO, bringing European delegations to Moscow and Crimea, and targeting "national parliaments of the EU" with resolutions to end EU sanctions on Russia and to grant recognition to Russia's annexation of Crimea.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Internal emails, including some from Mirzakhanyan, document substantial payments to EU politicians made in exchange for pro-Kremlin motions in their home countries, and to Manuel Ochsenreiter for publishing pro-Russian propaganda in his *Zuerst!* magazine.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In August 2023 a journalist investigation was published by *The Insider*, describing how money was funnelled from Moscow to AfD politicians who initiated a constitutional complaint in Germany against the supplies of weapons for Ukraine.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD supported peace negotiations on the Russo-Ukrainian War with the participation of Russia.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In October 2025 Georg Maier, the Interior Minister of Thuringia, raised concerns that the AfD might be using parliamentary inquiries to obtain information on critical infrastructure on behalf of the Kremlin.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] This includes detailed requests on transport and digital infrastructure, as well as water and energy supply, military capabilities, weak points and logistics.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD initially held a position of soft Euroscepticism by opposing the euro currency and eurozone bailouts, which the party saw as undermining European integration, but it was otherwise supportive of German membership of the European Union (EU).
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] During the 2021 party conference in Dresden, a majority of AfD members voted to include more hardline policies against the European Union including German withdrawal from the bloc in the party's manifesto ahead of the 2021 German federal election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Since 2025 the AfD has been working with Hungary's nationalist prime minister, Viktor Orbán.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Alice Weidel praised Hungary as a model for AfD, saying that AfD shares Hungary's opposition to illegal immigration and stance on the European Union.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In February 2025 Weidel stated about AfD's policy towards the European Union: "We should work together to reform the European Union at all costs.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party had previously been pro-Israel.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD supported the decision of US president Donald Trump to recognize Jerusalem as Israel's capital, as stated by AfD's Petr Bystron.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Despite AfD's pro-Israel stance, Israel has boycotted the party and has refused to hold ties with AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Following the October 7 attacks, the party supported cuts in German aid to Palestine via the UNRWA.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2024, AfD reversed its previously pro-Israel position, with co-leader Tino Chrupalla calling for an end to Germany's current relationship with Israel, which Chrupalla described as "one-sided", as well as an end to arms exports to Israel during the Gaza war.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] This decision drew criticism from some other members of the AfD parliamentary group, suggesting a continued internal divide on the issue.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Chrupalla criticised the German government's support for Israel during the war and rejected "blanket" Islamophobia.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Some AfD members referred to Israel's conduct as constituting genocide in Gaza.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Nevertheless, in January 2025, the other co-leader, Alice Weidel, affirmed her support for Israel, but noted that she "didn't know how she would solve this conflict".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Chrupalla and Weidel have been described as divided on the issue of Israel, with Weidel continuing to affirm German support for Israel's right to self-defence.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] At the start of the Twelve-Day War between Israel and Iran in June 2025, AfD foreign policy spokesperson Markus Frohnmaier expressed support for a diplomatic solution and called on both sides to cease hostilities, while insisting that Iran should not pursue a nuclear weapons programme.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2018 and 2019, AfD Bundestag members visited Ba'athist Syria, meeting with senior officials from the government of Bashar al-Assad and advocating for the return of Syrian refugees.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2026, in the midst of the 2026 Iran war, party leader Tino Chrupalla praised Spain's refusal to allow American forces to use its military bases for the conflict, and urged Germany to follow Spain's example.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] He further proposed ending the stationing of US forces in Germany, as well as their nuclear weapons presence in the country.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party had previously demanded the German government to strip the "developing country" status for China, voicing opposition to "Chinese economic espionage" and opposing Chinese state-owned company COSCO Shipping buying of a stake in the Port of Hamburg.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] However, it started changing its position in 2023, with AfD's Bundestag caucus accusing foreign minister Annalena Baerbock and economic affairs minister Robert Habeck of launching an "economic war" against China.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has also criticised restrictions on the use of 5G material from Chinese companies Huawei and ZTE.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD leader Tino Chrupalla has also voiced opposition to restrictions on Chinese technology and backed Chinese foreign minister Qin Gang on his peace-brokering efforts for Russia's invasion of Ukraine.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD currently calls for closer economic, cultural and scientific relations with China.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Nevertheless, in their manifesto for the 2025 federal election, AfD has also called for limits in the involvement of Chinese companies in Germany's seaports and digital infrastructure.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] It is also opposed to further development aid, including those that would benefit climate change programs or Chinese students in Germany.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] After joining the parliament with more than 90 representatives in the 2017 federal election, the party received more than 70 million euros per year; this probably rose to more than 100 million euros per year from 2019 onward.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party has also established and acknowledged a foundation for political education, and other purposes, close to the party but organized separately, which may be able to claim up to 80 million euros per year.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] This foundation would need to be acknowledged by the federal parliament in Germany first, but it has a legal claim to these subsidies.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In 2018 the Alternative for Germany donation scandal became public, as federal and European Parliament politicians Alice Weidel, Jörg Meuthen, Marcus Pretzell, and Guido Reil had profited from illegal and unnamed donations from non-EU countries.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The acceptance of donations from non-EU countries is prohibited for German parties and politicians.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Young Alternative for Germany (German: *Junge Alternative für Deutschland*, JA) was founded in 2013 as the youth organisation of AfD, while remaining legally independent from its mother party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In view of JA's independence, it has been regarded by some in AfD's hierarchy as being somewhat wayward, with JA repeatedly accused of being "too far-right", politically regressive and antifeminist by the German mainstream media.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In December 2024 the main party of the AfD announced its intention to cut ties with the JA in connection to its classification by the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD leadership are planning to found a new organisation as its youth wing.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] On 12 January 2025, AfD leadership voted to formally replace the JA as its youth organisation.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Following the 2014 European Parliament election on 12 June, AfD was accepted into the European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR) group in the European Parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In February 2016, AfD announced a closer cooperation with the right-wing populist party Freedom Party of Austria (FPÖ), which was a member of the Europe of Nations and Freedom (ENF) group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] On 8 March 2016, the bureau of the ECR group began motions to exclude AfD MEPs from their group due to the party's links with the far-right FPÖ and controversial remarks by two party leaders about shooting immigrants.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] MEP Beatrix von Storch pre-empted her imminent expulsion by leaving the ECR group to join the Europe of Freedom and Direct Democracy group on 8 April, and Marcus Pretzell was expelled from the ECR group on 12 April 2016.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] During the party convention on 30 April 2016, Pretzell announced his intention to join the Europe of Nations and Freedom group, although he subsequently left AfD to join Petry's Blue Party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In April 2019, Jörg Meuthen appeared alongside Northern League leader Matteo Salvini, National Rally leader Marine Le Pen, and politicians from the Danish People's Party and FPÖ to announce the formation of a new European political alliance.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD later joined this group in the European Parliament, which was ultimately named the Identity and Democracy group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In July 2023, the AfD joined the Identity and Democracy Party, the European political party affiliated with this group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The AfD initially maintained close cooperation with the French National Rally and Marine Le Pen.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In February 2024, it was reported that the relations between the two parties had become strained after AfD spokesmen attended the 2023 Potsdam far-right meeting.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In response, the AfD's leadership held a meeting with Le Pen and denied endorsing the words of some of the people at the meeting.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The Flemish Vlaams Belang criticised Krah's words as "increasingly problematic" but declined to immediately expel the AfD faction, stating they preferred to review the situation after the election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The Estonian EKRE and the FPÖ supported expelling Krah but opposed the expulsion of AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] After an internal meeting and vote, the Identity and Democracy board subsequently agreed to expel AfD, with group leader Marco Zanni citing Krah's interview, as well as allegations of Chinese and Russian espionage influence on AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The party consequently moved to non-inscrits.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Following the decision, AfD said they would negotiate to rejoin the group and announced Krah would not sit with the AfD faction in the European Parliament after the election.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Following the 2024 European Parliament election, the AfD began negotiations with several of these parties to form a new European Parliament group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Although the AfD originally negotiated with S.O.S.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Romania, it later rejected S.O.S.'s attempt to join the group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The KKP was also eventually rejected from the group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] Despite the Czech SPD's prior declaration that it would not sit with the AfD, and past opposition by Poland's New Hope to cooperation with the AfD, both parties ultimately joined the AfD-led Europe of Sovereign Nations group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In August 2024, AfD also formed the Europe of Sovereign Nations party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In the United States, AfD has connections with former Department of Government Efficiency leader Elon Musk and groups associated with the Republican Party, particularly the Young Republicans.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In response to the German domestic intelligence agency 2025 classification of the party as a "confirmed right-wing extremist endeavor" permitting monitoring of it, US Vice President JD Vance wrote, "The West tore down the Berlin Wall together.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] And it has been rebuilt – not by the Soviets or the Russians, but by the German establishment." US secretary of state Marco Rubio also wrote "Germany just gave its spy agency new powers to surveil the opposition.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has contacts with the People's Party of Canada through the AfD MEP Christine Anderson.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] The former President of Switzerland, Ueli Maurer of the Swiss People's Party, has endorsed the 2025 AfD election campaign and addressed AfD events.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] In February 2025, Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orbán and Weidel announced the start of cooperation between AfD and Fidesz.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] During its 2025 German federal election campaign, the AfD also received support from the Spanish Vox party and the Alliance of Independent Social Democrats in Bosnia and Herzegovina.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p02] AfD has some links with the UK Homeland Party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] At the outset, AfD presented itself as conservative and middle-class, catering to a well-educated demographic; around two-thirds of supporters listed on its website in the early days held doctorates, leading to AfD being nicknamed the "professors' party" in its early days.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The party was described as professors and academics who dislike the compromises inflicted on their purist theories by German party politics.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] 86% of the party's initial supporters were male.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Outside the Berlin hotel where the party held its inaugural meeting, it has been alleged that copies of *Junge Freiheit*, a weekly that is also popular with the far right, were being handed out.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The *Rheinische Post* pointed out that some AfD members and supporters write for the conservative paper.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] There was also a protest outside the venue of the party's inaugural meeting by Andreas Storr, a National Democratic Party of Germany (NPD) representative in the Landtag of Saxony, as the NPD sees AfD as a rival for Eurosceptic votes.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] In 2013, AfD party organizers sent out the message that they are not trying to attract right-wing radicals and toned down rhetoric on their Facebook page following media allegations that it too closely evoked the language of the far right.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] At that time, AfD checked applicants for membership to exclude far-right and former NPD members who support the anti-euro policy.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The former party chairman Bernd Lucke stated that "[t]he applause is coming from the wrong side", regarding praise his party gained from the NPD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Members of Alliance 90/Green Party have accused AfD of pandering to xenophobic and nationalistic sentiments.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] There have been altercations between AfD members and Green Youth members.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Following the 2013 federal election, the anti-Islam German Freedom Party unilaterally pledged to support AfD in the 2014 elections and concentrate its efforts on local elections only.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Bernd Lucke responded by saying that the German Freedom Party's support was unwanted and sent a letter to AfD party associations recommending a hiring freeze.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] In 2018 Tino Chrupalla, the current co-leader of AfD, gave an interview to holocaust denier, antisemite and right-wing extremist Nikolai Nerling, which was uploaded to YouTube.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] It was staged as having occurred by chance, but an earlier shot in the video reveals Chrupalla waiting in the background.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] As such, the interview was cited in the 2019 Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution report on AfD as evidence of the party's "Connections to the framework of a so-called new right or right-wing populist 'resistance milieu'".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] On 24 June 2024 it was announced that two parliamentary groups consisting of members of the AfD and Die Heimat formerly the NPD, had been formed in the Brandenburg town of Lauchhammer and the district of Oberspreewald-Lausitz.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] In Lauchhammer, the joint parliamentary group will be represented in the town council under the name "AfDplus", while the "Heimat & Zukunft" parliamentary group has been formed in the district council of Oberspreewald-Lausitz.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Thomas Gürtler from *Die Heimat* will play a leading role in both bodies.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] This development is seen as the first official coalition between AfD and the far-right party *Die Heimat*.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The formation of the parliamentary groups was supported by statements made by AfD chairman Tino Chrupalla, who emphasised that there would be no "firewalls" to other parties at local level.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] In 2016 AfD MEP Marcus Pretzell was expelled from the party after he said that German borders should be defended from incursion by refugees "with armed force as a measure of last resort".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Petry later stated that no policeman "wants to fire on a refugee and I don't want that either" but that border police must follow the law to maintain the integrity of European borders.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Afterwards, Petry made several attempts to justify these statements.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] In response to the Pegida movement and demonstrations, members of AfD have expressed different opinions of it, with Lucke describing the movement as "a sign that these people do not feel their concerns are understood by politicians".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] In response to the CDU Interior Minister Thomas de Maizière alleging an "overlap" between Pegida rallies and AfD, Alexander Gauland stated that AfD are "natural allies of this movement".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Hans-Olaf Henkel asked members of the party not to join the demonstrations, telling *Der Tagesspiegel* that he believed it could not be ruled out that they had "xenophobic or even racist connotations".
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] A straw poll by *The Economist* found that nine out of ten Pegida protesters would back the AfD.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The speech was widely criticised as antisemitic or neo-Nazi, among others by Jewish leaders in Germany.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Within AfD, he was described by his party chairwoman, Frauke Petry, as a "burden to the party", while other members of the party, such as Alexander Gauland, said that they found no antisemitism in the speech.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] In February 2017, AfD leaders asked for Höcke to be expelled from the party due to his speech.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The arbitration committee of AfD in Thuringia was set to rule on the leaders' request.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] In May 2018, an AfD tribunal ruled that Höcke was allowed to stay in the party.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The AfD politician Matthias Helferich had described himself in social media messages as the "friendly face of the ns [*sic*]," referring to National Socialism.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Helferich also called himself a "democratic Freisler," referring to a Nazi-era judge.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The event triggered the 2024 German anti-extremism protests.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] In May 2024, Höcke was convicted and fined €13,000 by the state court in Halle for deliberately using a banned slogan *"Alles für Deutschland"*, associated with the Nazi Party's paramilitary wing, in a May 2021 campaign speech.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] In the same month, the party member Maximilian Krah defence of the *Waffen-SS* caused controversy.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Following the 2025 federal election it was confirmed that Maximillian Krah and Matthias Helferich would be joining the parliament.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] On 2 May 2025 the German domestic intelligence agency, Bundesamt für Verfassungsschutz (BfV), published a report spanning 1,100 pages which sought to assess whether the AfD should be designated as an 'extremist' group.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Central to its thesis was the party's anti-Muslim stance, and it favouring national and ethnic Germans over migrants.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] AfD denounced its designation as a politically motivated attempt to discredit and criminalize it.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The designation opens the possibility of civil servants belonging to the AfD facing dismissal depending on their role within the entity, according to the country's interior ministry.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] AfD members and activists were listed as keeping close ties with Russian politicians and receiving financial benefits in an OCCRP investigation of Russia's International Agency for Current Policy.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The AfD Politicians Eugen Schmidt, Olga Petersen, and Ulrich Oehme founded the "Association for the Prevention of Discrimination and Exclusion of Russian-Germans and Russian-speaking Fellow Citizens in Germany" (Vadar e.V.) in June 2022.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The association attests that Germany has an "anti-Russian mood" and wants to offer legal help to "Russian-Germans and Russian-speaking fellow citizens" who would be discriminated against or excluded by the war of aggression.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The association says it financed the legal representation of pro-Russian influencer Alina Lipp and is opposed to the German ban on the Russian military and propaganda symbol *Z*.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] The association denies Russian war crimes in the Russo-Ukrainian War.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] According to a report in the *Sächsische Zeitung*, Vadar shares a bank account with an institution that is majority Russian-owned.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] According to German public broadcaster ARD, German security authorities are investigating the association connections to Russian authorities.
[src:alliance-for-direct-democracy-in-europe/alternative-for-germany-p03] Internal emails, including some from Mirzakhanyan, document substantial payments to EU politicians made in exchange for pro-Kremlin motions in their home countries, and to journalist and AfD member Manuel Ochsenreiter for publishing pro-Russian propaganda in his *Zuerst!* magazine.
